All lectures crypto, game theory, control optimization, algorithms - all taught as separate entities with no mention of a unifying theory.
Not that its any new but the way mathematics is taught at even some of the best universities in the world is horrific.
Had I asked myself 4 yrs ago during my game theory class - so tell me the significance of nash's contributions- I wudnt have a clue.
A trick I have learnt is not be bothered with their terminologies in mathematical work. Just get the gist of what the man is trying to do.
Not that I am too fond of calculus, sometimes I feel it is presented in a very non intuitive way scaring people off at early stages
I aint too sure why there was almost zero calculus in my master's level game theory class. I feel cheated right now.
The mathematical rigour of some of the work in game theory took me by complete surprise. I really wasn't ready for that I guess.
